class.name: Built-up
class.definition: The land covered by buildings, roads and artificial surfaced ar-eas. Different types of build-up are included in this class (i.e. urban, airports, oilfields). Non-vegetated areas are character-ized by NDVI values close to zero.

class.name: Roads
class.definition: Linear artificial structures, mainly major roads (motor-ways, primary roads).

class.name: Tree orchards
class.definition: Orchards are areas cultivated for the production of fruits, nuts, and other type of plantations. Areas covered by orchards are characterized by NDVI values very similar to the one shown by tree closed land cover class.

class.name: Herbaceous crops irrigated
class.definition: Agricultural areas characterized by ex-tensive irrigational facilities. The pres-ence channels for irrigation is a distinc-tive factor of this land cover class. The greenness associated with irrigated sites is generally independent of rainfall. Irri-gated crops have 2 higher peaks corre-sponding to the two main crop seasons: Kharif (first sowing season from April – June and harvested during October – December) with the main crops such as rice, sugarcane, cotton and maize and Rabi (second sowing season from Octo-ber – December and harvested in April – May) with main crops such as cereals and oil seeds.

class.name: Herbaceous crops rainfed
class.definition: Rainfed agricul-ture relies only on rainfall for wa-ter, therefore NDVI values strictly depend on rainfall pat-tern over the year but the gen-eral aspect re-flects the two main crop sea-sons.

class.name: Herbaceous crops in flood plain
class.definition: Herbaceous crop located only in proximity of the riverbed is termed as crop in floodplain. The water supply is provided either by irrigation or by the annual floods. Crop in flood-plain includes herbaceous crop irrigated in flood plain and herbaceous crop post-flooding

class.name: Herbaceous natural vegetation
class.definition: Relatively dense herba-ceous natural vegetation, occasionally with sparse shrubs and trees. NDVI values are very low throughout the year

class.name: Shrubs sparse natural vegetation
class.definition: Natural open shrubs, occasionally with sparse or closed herba-ceous vegetation cov-er, with percentage cover varying from 10 to 60%.

class.name: Shrubs dense natural vegetation
class.definition: Natural closed shrubs with shrubs percentage cover of more than 60%. In Punjab the forest cover is limited, and it is pre-dominantly scrub forest

class.name: Shrubs in temporary wet soil
class.definition: This class includes areas mainly covered by shrubs of-ten with herbaceous vegeta-tion, usually flooded or liable to flooding by fresh, stagnant or circulating water.

class.name: Trees sparse natural vegetation
class.definition: Natural open trees, occasionally with sparse or closed her-baceous vegetation cover, with percent-age cover varying from 10 to 60%.

class.name: Tree forest plantations
class.definition: Tree forest plantation refers to governmental plantation. This class can be identified with large area and regular shape

class.name: Trees dense natural vegetation
class.definition: Natural closed trees with tree percentage cover of more than 60%. In Punjab the forest cover is limited, and it is predomi-nantly scrub forest. The co-niferous forests are mainly present in the northern mountainous areas.

class.name: Sand dunes
class.definition: Bare area/undifferentiated area not used for cultivation and usually devoid of grass and shrub cover. Non-vegetated areas are charac-terized by NDVI values close to zero.

class.name: Bare soil
class.definition: Bare area/undifferentiated area not used for cultivation and usually devoid of grass and shrub cover. Non-vegetated ar-eas are characterized by NDVI values close to zero.

class.name: Bare soil in temporary wet
class.definition: Part of the river bed flooded during the rainy season (flood plain).

class.name: Water bodies
class.definition: Natural and artificial non-perennial fresh water body (flowing and standing).

class.name: Wetlands
class.definition: Wetlands are herbaceous vege-tation with cover ranging from 60% to 100% found in flood-ed/wet areas, sometimes asso-ciated with shrubs. NDVI values are higher during the summer season when the progressive reduction of water surface leaves space to the natural vegetation growth.

class.name: Evergreen hill forest
class.definition: Natural forest area within the reserve forest boundary and protected forest boundary of Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) is known as hill forest. It consists of moist tropical evergreen and semi-evergreen trees. Tree cover ranges from 80% - 100% and top canopy of trees reach a height of 25-62 m.

class.name: Forest plantation
class.definition: The area where trees are planted for high volume of timber and wood under long-term or short- term management. Trees are generally even- aged, planted in rows in a large enough area. Tree height ranges 5 – 40 m and cover ranges 80% - 100%. Agroforestry can also be incorporated with this class.

class.name: Swamp forest
class.definition: Land dominated by evergreen trees which are inundated with freshwater seasonally. Trees grows to about 15–25 m in height with a large canopy. Root of these trees are in two level. One in the ground, and another in the mid-level which is used while the forest is flooded in the monsoon time. Main species are Koroch and Hizal tree

class.name: Rubber plantation
class.definition: The large area where rubber (Hevea brasiliensis) is planted for latex production. Trees are planted in well-drained soil with 3%-32% slope. It is broadleaved, deciduous in the drier month for a very short period. It grows 30 – 40 m and cover ranging from 80% – 100%.

class.name: Mangrove forest
class.definition: The geographical area dominated by halophytic trees with a canopy cover of 85% to 100% and tree height vary from 5m - 17m. The forest floor inundated twice daily by brackish water. The forest is intersected by numerous rivers and creeks.

class.name: Plain land forest (sal forest)
class.definition: Land dominated with tropical moist deciduous forests are known as plain land sal forest. The main species is Sal (Shorea robusta) and its occurrence is 80% - 100% within the patches. Tree height is 5 -25 m and it covers ranging from 60% - 100%.

class.name: Orchards & other plantations (trees)
class.definition: Land dominated with tree species for harvesting fruits. In general, trees are even-aged, planted and managed in rows and cover a large enough area. Marginal land plantations (road, railway, embankment, and canal side) are also included in this class.

class.name: Mangrove plantation
class.definition: Mangrove plantations on newly accreted land in the estuaries of the Bay of Bengal to provide protection against natural calamities and land erosion.

class.name: Bamboo forest
class.definition: Bamboo forest is woody grass of more than 4 m and its occurrence is more than 80% within the patches. It naturally occurs and it covers ranging from 80% - 100%. It is perennial evergreen and it grows up to 15 m. The bamboo resources in the villages areas not included in this class.

class.name: Orchards & other plantations (shrubs)
class.definition: Land dominated by shrubs which are cultivated and managed for fruits and leaf harvesting. This class mainly includes tea gardens. The use of shade trees in tea cultivation is a vital and integral component.

class.name: Rivers/khals
class.definition: Natural water courses serving as water drainage channels.

class.name: Single crop
class.definition: This class includes permanent agriculture lands cultivated with a single herbaceous crop in a year and the same herbaceous crop is cultivated in the same land for several years. Fields may be flooded in monsoon but not in the growing season.

class.name: Herb dominated area
class.definition: The geographic area which is dominated by grass with very little to no woody vegetation is called herb dominated area. These types of vegetation are generally found in newly accreted land, year round fallow land or adjacent to the international boundary of Bangladesh. The coverage is 20 - 100%.

class.name: Multiple crop
class.definition: This class includes permanent agriculture lands which are cultivated with more than one herbaceous crop (Two or Three) in different growing season sequentially (crop diversified in time) within a year and the same crop rotation is practiced in the same land for several years.

class.name: Shifting cultivation
class.definition: This  class includes lands where herbaceous crops are cultivated temporarily, then abandoned and allowed to return to their natural vegetation while the farmer moves on to another area.

class.name: Baor
class.definition: Baor is a natural water body and a dead section of a river where it has changed its course. It normally is a part of the floodplain of the river to which inlets and outlets connect it.

class.name: Perennial beels/haors
class.definition: Natural water reservoir, billabong or a lake-like wetland with static water. It becomes very extensive water body in the monsoon and dries up mostly in the post-monsoon period.

class.name: Standing artificial water body - lake
class.definition: Artificial/Natural standing water reservoir that is bigger than a pond. It is an area of variable size filled with water, localized in a basin, that is surrounded by land, apart from any river or other outlet that serves to feed or drain the lake.

class.name: Ponds
class.definition: pond is a human-constructed body of standing water with an area of variable size that is usually smaller than a lake.

class.name: Brackish water aquaculture
class.definition: Large brackish water ponds used for year round brackish water aquaculture.

class.name: Fresh water aquaculture
class.definition: Fresh water ponds used for year round aquaculture.

class.name: Mud flats or inter tidal areas
class.definition: Mud flats or intertidal areas are wet land soil near the estuary. It is submerged and exposed twice daily by tidal water.

class.name: Built-up non-linear
class.definition: This category describes built-up areas where non-linear artificial constructions cover the land with an impervious surface.

class.name: Beach/sand bar
class.definition: Beaches are narrow, gently sloping strip of natural land that lies along the coast and usually consists of loose particles, which are composed of sand. Sand bar are sand deposits within the river channels or in the estuary which are emerging as islands

class.name: Dump sites/ extraction sites
class.definition: Extraction site is defined by the absence of the original natural (semi-natural) cover or water surface and land cover, rock or earthy materials are removed by human activity or machinery.

class.name: River banks
class.definition: The river bank is the natural land alongside the bed of a river which is usually consists of soil and sand deposits and inundated when water course flows with full capacity.

class.name: Air port
class.definition: Built-up areas with facilities for flights to take off and land.

class.name: Salt pans
class.definition: Land used for salt production from seawater by solar evaporation

class.name: Rural settlement
class.definition: Geographic areas of clustered or linear rural dwelling (mainly wooden and tin roof) covered by fruit trees and other plantation and functionally linked with small scale vegetables gardens, open spaces and ponds around the dwellings. Rural markets or growth centers within the rural environment are also included in this class.

class.name: Swap plantation
class.definition: The land dominated by evergreen trees, which are cultivated and inundated in monsoon with freshwater, is known as Swamp Plantation. Trees grows to about 5-45m in height with a large canopy.

class.name: Shrubs with scattered trees
class.definition: This class includes natural woody vegetation of less than 5 m in height. The uppermost canopy layer may be dominated by trees. The shrub foliage can be either evergreen or deciduous.

class.name: Swamp reed land
class.definition: The geographical area which is dominated by reed shrub and the root system is influenced by the fresh water is known as swamp reed land.

class.name: Brickfields
class.definition: Geographic  areas used for bricks production

name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Artificial surfaces (including urban and associated areas)
class.definition: The category is composed of any type of artificial surfaces
class.description: The class is composed of any type of areas with a predominant artificial surface. Any urban or related feature is included in this class, for example, urban parks (parks, parkland and laws). The class also includes industrial areas, and waste dump deposit and extraction sites.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Herbaceous crops
class.definition: The category is composed of a main layer of cultivated herbaceous plants.
class.description: The class is composed of a main layer of cultivated herbaceous plants (graminoids or forbs). It includes herbaceous crops used for hay. All the non-perennial crops that do not last for more than two growing seasons and crops like sugar cane, where the upper part of the plant is regularly harvested while the root system can remain for more than one year in the field, are included in this class.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Woody crops
class.definition: The category is composed of a main layer of cultivated tree or shrub plants.
class.description: The class is composed of a main layer of permanent crops (trees or shrub crops) and includes all types of orchards and plantations (fruit trees, coffee and tea plantation, oil palms, rubber plantation, Christmas trees, etc.).
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Multiple or layered crops
class.definition: The category is composed of at least two layers of cultivated woody and herbaceous plants or different layers of cultivated plants combined with natural vegetation.
class.description: This class combine two different land cover situations: 1. Two layers of different crops. A common case is the presence of one layer of woody crops (trees or shrubs) and another layer of herbaceous crop, e.g., wheat fields with olive trees in the Mediterranean area and intense horticulture, or oasis or typical coastal agriculture in Africa, where herbaceous fields are covered by palm trees. 2. Presence of one important layer of natural vegetation (mainly trees) that covers one layer of cultivated crops. Coffee plantations shadowed by natural trees in the equatorial area of Africa are a typical example.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Grassland
class.definition: The category is composed of a main layer of natural herbaceous vegetation with a cover from 10 to 100 per cent.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area dominated by natural herbaceous plants (grasslands, prairies, steppes and savannahs) with a cover of 10 per cent or more, irrespective of different human and/or animal activities, such as grazing or selective fire management. Woody plants (trees and/or shrubs) can be present, assuming their cover is less that 10 per cent.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Trees covered areas
class.definition: The category is composed of a main layer of natural trees with a cover from 10 to 100 per cent.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area dominated by natural tree plants with a cover of 10 per cent or more. Other types of plants (shrubs and/or herbs) can be present, even with a density higher than that of trees. Areas planted with trees for afforestation purposes and forest plantations are included in this class. This class includes areas seasonally or permanently flooded with freshwater. It excludes coastal mangroves (→07).
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Mangroves
class.definition: The category is composed of natural trees with a cover from 10 to 100 per cent in aquatic or regularly flooded areas in salt and brackish water.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area dominated by woody vegetation (trees and/or shrubs) with a cover of 10 per cent or more that is permanently or regularly flooded by salt and/or brackish water located in the coastal areas or in the deltas of rivers.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Shrub covered areas
class.definition: The category is composed of a main layer of natural shrubs with a cover from 10 to 100 per cent.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area dominated by natural shrubs having a cover of 10 per cent or more. Trees can be present in scattered form if their cover is less than 10 per cent. Herbaceous plants can also be present at any density. The class includes shrub-covered areas permanently or regularly flooded by inland fresh water. It excludes shrubs flooded by salt or brackish water in coastal areas (→07).
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Shrubs and/or herbaceous vegetation, aquatic or regularly flooded
class.definition: The category is composed of natural shrubs or herbs with a cover from 10 to 100 percent in aquatic or regularly flooded areas with water persistence from 2 to 12 months per year.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area dominated by natural herbaceous vegetation (cover of 10 per cent or more) that is permanently or regularly flooded by fresh or rackish water (swamps, marsh areas, etc.). Flooding must persist for at least two months per year to be considered regular. Woody vegetation (trees and/or shrubs) can be present if their cover is less than 10 per cent.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Sparsely natural vegetated areas
class.definition: The category is composed of any type of natural vegetation (all growth forms) with a cover from 2 to 10 per cent.
class.description: This class includes any geographical areas were the cover of natural vegetation is between 2 per cent and 10 per cent. This includes permanently or regularly flooded areas.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Terrestrial barren land
class.definition: The category is composed of abiotic natural surfaces.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area dominated by natural abiotic surfaces (bare soil, sand, rocks, etc.) where the natural vegetation is absent or almost absent (covers less than 2 per cent). The class includes areas regularly flooded by inland water (lake shores, river banks, salt flats, etc.). It excludes coastal areas affected by the tidal movement of saltwater (→14).
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Permanent snow and glaciers
class.definition: The category is composed of abiotic natural surfaces.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area covered by snow or glaciers persistently for 10 months or more.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Inland water bodies
class.definition: The category is composed of any type of inland water body with a water persistence of 12 months per year.
class.description: This class includes any geographical area covered for most of the year by inland water bodies. In some cases, the water can be frozen for part of the year (less than 10 months). Because the geographical extent of water bodies can change, boundaries must be set consistently with those set by class 11, according to the dominant situation during the year and/or across multiple years.
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Coastal water bodies and intertidal areas
class.definition: The category is composed on the basis of geographical features in relation to the sea (lagoons and estuaries) and abiotic surfaces subject to water persistence (intertidal variations).
class.description: The class is defined on the basis of geographical features of the land in relation to the sea (coastal water bodies, i.e., lagoons and estuaries) and abiotic surfaces subject to water persistence (intertidal areas, i.e., coastal flats and coral reefs).
class.legend_Name: System of Environmental-Economic Accounting (SEEA) land cover legend

class.name: Mineral extraction
class.definition: Areas with open-pit extraction of construction material (sand pits, quarries) or other minerals (open-cast mines).Includes flooded gravel pits, except for river-bed extraction.

class.name: Dump site
class.definition: Public, industrial or mine dumpsites.

class.name: Construction sites
class.definition: Spaces under construction development, soil or bed rock excavations, earthworks.

class.name: Urban park
class.definition: Areas with vegetation within urban fabric, includes parks and cemeteries with vegetation, and mansions and their grounds.

class.name: Sport facilities
class.definition: Camping grounds, sports grounds, leisure parks, golf courses, race courses, etc. Includes formal parks not surrounded by urban areas.

class.name: Non irrigated arable land
class.definition: Cereals, legumes, fodder crops, root crops and fallow land. Includes flowers and fruit trees (nurseries cultivation) and vegetables, whether open field, under plastic or glass (includes market gardening). Includes aromatic, medicinal and culinary plants. Does not include permanent pastures.

class.name: Permanently irrigated land
class.definition: Crops irrigated permanently or periodically, using a permanent infrastructure (irrigation channels, drainage network).Most of these crops cannot be cultivated without an artificial water supply. Does not include sporadically irrigated land.

class.name: Rice fields
class.definition: Land prepared for rice cultivation. Flat surfaces with irrigation channels. Surfaces periodically flooded.

class.name: Vineyards
class.definition: Areas planted with vines.

class.name: Fruit trees and berry plantation
class.definition: Parcels planted with fruit trees or shrubs: single or mixed fruit species, fruit trees associated with permanently grassed surfaces. Includes chestnut and walnut groves.

class.name: Olives groves
class.definition: Areas planted with olive trees, including mixed occurrence of olive trees and vines on the same parcel.

class.name: Pasture
class.definition: Dense grass, cover of floral composition, dominated by graminacea, not under a rotation system. Mainly for grazing, but the fodder maybe harvested mechanically. Includes areas with hedges (bocage).

class.name: Annual crops associated with permanent crops
class.definition: Non-permanent crops (arable land or pasture) associated with permanent crops on the same parcel.

class.name: Complex cultivation pattern
class.definition: Juxtaposition of small parcels of diverse annual crops, pasture and/or permanent crops.

class.name: Land principally occupied by agriculture with signficant areas of natural vegetation
class.definition: Areas principally occupied by agriculture, interspersed with significant natural areas.

class.name: Agroforestry areas
class.definition: Annual crops or grazing land under the wooded cover of forestry species.

class.name: Broadleaved forest
class.definition: Vegetation formation composed principally of trees, including shrub and bush under storeys, where broad-leaved species predominate.

class.name: Coniferous forest
class.definition: Vegetation formation composed principally of trees, including shrub and bush under storeys, where coniferous species predominate.

class.name: Mixed forest
class.definition: Vegetation formation composed principally of trees, including shrub and bush under storeys, where neither broad-leaved nor coniferous species predominate.

class.name: Natural grassland
class.definition: Low productivity grassland. Often situated in areas of rough, uneven ground. Frequently includes rocky areas, briars and heathland.

class.name: Moors and heathland
class.definition: Vegetation with low and closed cover, dominated by bushes, shrubs and herbaceous plants (heather, briars, broom, gorse, laburnum, etc.).

class.name: Sclerophillous vegetation
class.definition: Bushy sclerophyllous vegetation, includes maquis and garrigue. In case of shrub vegetation areas composed of sclerophyllous species such as Juniperus oxycedrus and heathland species such as Buxus spp. or Ostrya carpinifolia with no visible dominance (each species occupy about 50% of the area), priority will be given to sclerophyllous vegetation and the whole area will be assigned class 323.

class.name: Transitional woodland-scrub
class.definition: Bushy or herbaceous vegetation with scattered trees. Can represent either woodland degradation or forest regeneration/recolonisation.

class.name: Sparse vegetation
class.definition: Beaches, dunes and expanses of sand or pebbles in coastal or continental locations, including beds of stream channels with torrential regime.

class.name: Bare rocks
class.definition: Scree, clifs, rock outcrops, including active erosion, rocks and reef flats situated above the high-water mark.

class.name: Sparsely vegetated areas
class.definition: Includes steppes, tundra and badlands. Scattered high-altitude vegetation.

class.name: Brunt areas
class.definition: Areas affected by recent fires, still mainly black.

class.name: Glaciers and perennial snow
class.definition: Land covered by glaciers or permanent snowfields

class.name: Inland marches
class.definition: Low-lying land usually flooded in winter, and more or less saturated by water all year round.

class.name: Peat bogs
class.definition: Peatland consisting mainly of decomposed moss and vegetable matter.

class.name: Salt marshes
class.definition: Vegetated low-lying areas, above the high-tide line, susceptible to flooding by sea water. Often, in the process of filling in, gradually being colonized by halophilic plants.

class.name: Salines
class.definition: Salt-pans, active or in process of abandonment. Sections of salt marsh exploited for the production of salt by evaporation. They are clearly distinguishable from the rest of the marsh by their parcellation and embankment systems.

class.name: Intertidal flats
class.definition: Generally unvegetated expanses of mud, sand or rock lying between high and low water marks. 0 m contour on maps.

class.name: Water course
class.definition: Natural or artificial water-courses serving as water drainage channels. Includes canals. Minimum width for inclusion: 100 m.

class.name: Water bodies
class.definition: Natural or artificial stretches of water.

class.name: Coastal lagoons
class.definition: Stretches of salt or brackish water in coastal areas which are separated from the sea by a tongue of land or other similar topography. These water bodies can be connected to the sea at limited points, either permanently or for parts of the year only.

class.name: Estuaries
class.definition: The mouth of a river within which the tide ebbs and flows.

class.name: Sea and ocean
class.definition: Zone seaward of the lowest tide limit.

class.name: Urban dense
class.definition: Most of the land is covered by structures and the transport network. Building, roads and artificially surfaced areas cover more than 80 % of the total surface. Non-linear areas of vegetation and bare soil are exceptional.

class.name: Urban open
class.definition: Most of the land is covered by structures. Building, roads and artificially surfaced areas associated with vegetated areas and bare soil, which occupy discontinuous but significant surfaces.

class.name: Industrial
class.definition: Artificially surfaced areas (with concrete, asphalt, tarmacadam or stabilised, e.g. beaten earth) without vegetation occupy most of the area, which also contains buildings and/or vegetation.

class.name: Road and rail networks and associated areas
class.definition: Motorways and railways, including associated installations (stations, platforms, embankments). Minimum width for inclusion: 100 m.

class.name: Port areas
class.definition: Infrastructure of port areas, including quays, dockyards and marinas.

class.name: Airports
class.definition: Airports installations: runways, buildings and associated land.

class.name: Residential (urban or built up)
class.definition: Residential land uses range from high density, represented by the multiple-unit structures of urban cores, to low density, where houses are on lots of more than an acre, on the periphery of urban expansion.

name: Anderson land use and land cover classification legend

class.name: Commercial and services (urban or built up)
class.definition: Commercial areas are those used predominantly for the sale of products and services. They are often abutted by residential, agricultural, or other contrasting uses which help define them.

class.name: Industrial (urban or built up)
class.definition: Industrial areas include a wide array of land uses from light manufacturing to heavy manufacturing plants. Identification of light industries-those focused on design, assembly, finishing, processing, and packaging of products-can often be based on the type of building, parking, and shipping arrangements.

class.name: Transportation, communication and utilities
class.definition: The land uses included in the Transportation, Communications, and Utilities category occur to some degree within all of the other Urban or Builtup categories and actually can be found within many other categories.

class.name: Industrial and commercial
class.definition: The Industrial and Commercial Complexes category includes those industrial and commercial land uses that typically occur together or in close functional proximity. Such areas commonly are labeled with terminology such as "Industrial Park," but since functions such as warehousing, wholesaling, and occasionally retailing may be found in the same structures or nearby, the more inclusive category title has been adopted.

class.name: Mixed urban or built up land
class.definition: The Mixed Urban or Built-up category is used for a mixture of Level II Urban or Built-up uses where individual uses cannot be separated at mapping scale. Where more than one-third intermixture of another use or uses occurs in a specific area, it is classified as Mixed Urban or Built-up Land. Where the intermixed land use or uses total less than one-third of the specific area, the category appropriate to the  dominant land use is applied.

class.name: Other urban or built up land
class.definition: Other Urban or Built-up Land typically consists of uses such as golf driving ranges, zoos, urban parks, cemeteries, waste dumps, water-control structures and spillways, the extensive parts of such uses as golf courses and ski areas, and undeveloped land within an urban setting.

class.name: Cropland and pasture
class.definition: The several components of Cropland and Pasture now used for agricultural statistics include: crop land harvested, including bush fruits; cultivated summer-fallow and idle cropland; land on which crop failure occurs; cropland in soil-improvement grasses and legumes; cropland used only for pasture in rotation with crops; and past~re on land more or less permanently used for that purpose.

class.name: Horchards
class.definition: Orchards, groves, and vineyards produce the various fruit and nut crops. Nurseries and horticultural areas, which include floricultural and seed-and-sod areas and some greenhouses, are used perennially for those purposes.

class.name: Confined feeding operations
class.definition: Confined Feeding Operations are large, specialized livestock production enterprises, chiefly beef cattle feedlots, dairy operations with confined feeding, and large poultry farms, but also including hog feedlots. These operations have large animal populations restricted to relatively small areas.

class.name: Herbaceous rangeland
class.definition: The Herbaceous Rangeland category encompasses lands dominated by naturally occurring grasses and forbs as well as those areas of actual rangeland which have been modified to include grasses and forbs as their principal cover, when the land is managed for rangeland purposes and not managed using practices typical of pastureland.

class.name: Shrub and brush rangeland
class.definition: The typical shrub occurrences are found in those arid and semiarid regions characterized by such xerophytic vegetative types with woody stems as big sagebrush (Artemisia tridentata), shadscale , greasewood (Sarcobatus vermiculatus), or creosote bush (Larrea divaricata) andalso by the typical desert succulent xerophytes, such as the various forms of Cactus.

class.name: Deciduous forest
class.definition: Deciduous Forest Land includes all forested areas having a predominance of trees that lose their leaves at the end of the frost-free season or at the beginning of a dry season.

class.name: Evergreen forest
class.definition: Evergreen Forest Land includes all forested areas in which the trees are predominantly those which remain green throughout the year.

class.name: Mixed forrst
class.definition: Mixed Forest Land includes all forested areas where both evergreen and deciduous trees are growing and neither predominates.

class.name: Streams and canals
class.definition: The Streams and Canals category includes rivers, creeks, canals, and other linear water bodies. Where the water course is interrupted by a control structure, the impounded area will be placed in the Reservoirs category.

class.name: Lakes
class.definition: Lakes are nonflowing, naturally enclosed bodies of water, including regulated natural lakes but excluding reservoirs.

class.name: Reservoir
class.definition: Reservoirs are artificial impoundments of water used for irrigation, flood control, municipal water supplies, recreation, hydroelectric power generation, and so forth.

class.name: Bay and estuaries
class.definition: Bays and Estuaries are inlets or arms of the sea that extend inland.

class.name: Forested wetland
class.definition: Forested Wetlands are wetlands dominated by woody vegetation. Forested Wetland includes season-ally flooded bottomland hardwoods, mangrove swamps, shrub swamps, and wooded swamps ineluding those around bogs.

class.name: Non forested wetlands
class.definition: Non-forested Wetlands are dominated by wetland herbaceous vegetation or are nonvegetated.

class.name: Dry salt flats
class.definition: Dry Salt Flats occurring on the flat-floored bottoms of interior desert basins which do not qualify as Wetland are included in this category.

class.name: Beaches
class.definition: Beaches are the smooth sloping accumulations of sand and gravel along shorelines.

class.name: Sandy areas other than beaches
class.definition: Sandy Areas other than Beaches are composed primarily of dunes -accumulations of sand transported by the wind.

class.name: Bare rock
class.definition: The Bare Exposed Rock category includes areas of bedrock exposure, des,ert pavement, scarps, talus, slides, volcanic material, rock glaciers, and other accumulations of rock without vegetative cover, with the exception of such rock exposures occurring in tundra regions.

class.name: Strip mines, quarries and gravel pits
class.definition: Those extractive mining activities that have significant surface expression are included in this category.

class.name: Shrub and bush tundra
class.definition: The Shrub and Brush Tundra category consists of the various woody shrubs and brushy thickets found in the tundra environment.

class.name: Herbaceouse tundra
class.definition: Herbaceous Tundra is composed of various sedges, grasses, forbs, lichens, and mosses, all of which lack woody stems.

class.name: Bare ground tundra
class.definition: Wet Tundra is usually found in areas having little topographic relief.

class.name: Perennial snowfields
class.definition: The Bare Ground Tundra category is intended for those tundra occurrences which are less than one third of vegetation

class.name: Glaciers
class.definition: Glacial ice originates from the compaction of snow into firn and finally to ice under the weight of several successive annual accumulations.

class.name: Perennial snowfields
class.definition: Perennial Snowfields are accumulations of snow and firn that did not entirely melt during previous summers

class.name: Herbaceous rangeland/shrub and brush rangeland
class.definition: Mixed Rangeland

class.name: Dry salt flats/bare rock/strip mines, quarries and gravel pits
class.definition: The Mixed Barren Land category is used when a mixture of Barren Land features occurs and the dominant land use occupies less than two-thirds of the area.

class.name: Shrub and bush tundra/herbaceouse tundra/wet tundra
class.definition: The Mixed Tundra category is used for a mixture of the Level II Tundra occurrences where any particular type occupies less than two-thirds of the area of the mapping unit.

class.name: Deciduous forest

class.name: Evergreen forest

class.name: Flooded forest
class.definition: This forest type is found in Tonle Sap Lake. Most of the forests are low and disturbed. In many cases, there is only a mosaic remaining.

class.name: Forest regrowth

class.name: Urban areas
class.definition: Artificial surfaces with urban area geographical aspect including buildings, other constructions and other artificial surfaces.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Rural villages
class.definition: Artificial surfaces with rural area geographical aspect including buildings and other artificial surfaces.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Industrial and other
class.definition: Artificial surfaces including industrial areas and other artificial surfaces.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Infrastructure
class.definition: Artificial surfaces including infrastructure and other artificial surfaces.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Bomas
class.definition: This class describes the generic aspect of bomas. It is constituted by one mandatory stratum that defines the overall class structure. The strata is constituted by three basic elements built up, herbs and bare area.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Port
class.definition: It is a built up – nonlinear area for ships.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Airport
class.definition: It is a built-up nonlinear area which is used for flights to take off and land.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Builtup linear & others
class.definition: It corresponds to artificial surface which are built-up linear.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Dump sites - extraction sites
class.definition: Land used for disposal of waste materials is known as dump sites. Extraction sites are defined by the absence of the original land cover which is removed by human activity or machinery for extraction of sand, stone, mineral or coal.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Permanent waterbodies
class.definition: It corresponds to natural water bodies which are permanent feature in an area. They are further categorized based on water dynamics.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: River
class.definition: The rivers are natural water courses which serves as water drainage channels
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Lakes
class.definition: A natural standing water reservoir that is bigger than a pond and has an irregular shape. This class consists of one mandatory strata.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Seasonal waterbodies
class.definition: It corresponds to natural water bodies which are seasonal in an area. They are further categorized based on natural water body persistence.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: River bank
class.definition: The riverbank is the land alongside the bed of a river which is usually consists of soil and sand deposits and inundated when the river flows with the fully capacity. This class describe the generic aspect of riverbank. It is constituted by two mandatory strata that defines the overall class structure. The strata is constituted by one basic element water body.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Wadies
class.definition: This class describe the generic aspect of Wadi. It is constituted by two mandatory strata that defines the overall class structure. The strata is constituted by one basic element water body.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Lake shore
class.definition: This class describe the generic aspect of lake shores. It is constituted by two mandatory strata that defines the overall class structure. The strata is constituted by one basic element water body.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Artificial water bodies
class.definition: It corresponds to artificial water bodies which are permanent and/or seasonal feature in an area.
class.legend_Name: Legend for West Africa land cover reference system

class.name: Bushland dense
class.definition: Land not defined as "forest", spanning more than 0.5 ha with shrub height between 1-3 m and a cover of 40-100%. It does not include land that is predominantly under agricultural or urban land use.

class.name: Bushland open
class.definition: Land not defined as "forest", shrubs height between 1-3 m sometimes combined with trees. It does not include land that is predominantly under agricultural or urban land use. Used for hunting, recreation, and grazing.

class.name: Bushland scattered cultivation
class.definition: Includes shifting cultivation. Shrub height between 1-3 m with combined cover of rainfed herbaceous crop area.

class.name: Open land bare soil
class.definition: Natural bare surface around larger lakes and disturbed areas

class.name: Bushland thicket
class.definition: Land not defined as “Forest”, trees lower than 5 m and a canopy cover of 0.1-15%, or trees able to reach these thresholds with a combined cover of shrubs. It does not include land that is predominantly under agricultural or urban land use.

class.name: Cultivated land herbaceous crops
class.definition: Various herbaceous crops e.g. Cotton, vegetables, sisal, tobacco, flower plantations etc.

class.name: Cultivated land grain crops
class.definition: Various types of grass crops e.g., maize, wheat, millet, rice, sorghum.

class.name: Cultivated land wooded crops
class.definition: Monocultures and mixed crops of Tea, Cashew nuts, Cloves, mangoes, oranges etc.

class.name: Forest humid montane
class.definition: Land spanning more than 0.5 ha with trees that have heights of between 20-50m with combined cover of natural herbaceous growth form. Geographical aspect is catchment forest, ≥ 800 m asl

class.name: Forest lowland
class.definition: Woody growth form with the geographical aspect of groundwater forests and some coastal forests, < 800 m asl.

class.name: Forest mangrove
class.definition: Area of forest and other wooded land with mangrove vegetation along coastal areas

class.name: Forest plantation
class.definition: Cultivation of trees.

class.name: Grassland bushed
class.definition: Natural herbaceous area with combined cover of shrubs.

class.name: Grassland open
class.definition: Natural herbaceous area with cover of 10-100% and used for hunting, recreation and grazing.

class.name: Grassland scattered cropland
class.definition: Cultivated rainfed herbaceous crops with natural herbaceous cover.

class.name: Grassland wooded
class.definition: Natural herbaceous cover area with some tree cover of less than 30 %.

class.name: Open land ice cap / snow
class.definition: Area cover with snow/ice cap.

class.name: Cultivated land agro-forestry system
class.definition: Home gardens with multi-storey tree covers shading other crops e.g. Banana, Coffee, beans and yams.

class.name: Woodland closed
class.definition: Beekeeping, Hunting, Recreation, Grazing, Conservation, Timber production

class.name: Other areas
class.definition: Urban and rural built-up areas, air fields, infrastructure (power lines, railways, mining sites etc).

class.name: Open land rock outcrops
class.definition: Places dominated by rocks

class.name: Open land coastal bare land
class.definition: Bare area along coastal side e.g. beach.

class.name: Inland water
class.definition: Inland water bodies generally include major rivers, lakes and water reservoirs.

class.name: Water ocean
class.definition: Water bodies include oceans.

class.name: Water wetlands
class.definition: Water-logged that are seasonally inundated.

class.name: Forest
class.definition: Land spanning more than 0.5 ha with trees higher than 5 m and a canopy cover of more than 10%, or trees able to reach these thresholds in situ. It does not include land that is predominantly under agricultural or urban land use.

class.name: Cropland
class.definition: This category includes arable and tillage land, and agroforestry systems where vegetation falls below the thresholds used for the forest land category, consistent with the selection of national definitions.

class.name: Built-up
class.definition: Built-up areas refer to artificial structures such as towns, villages, industrial areas, airports, etc.

class.name: Water bodies
class.definition: Rivers are natural flowing water bodies and typically have elongated shapes. Lakes and ponds are perennial standing water bodies.

class.name: Other wooded land
class.definition: Land not classified as forest spanning more than 0.5 ha, having at least 20 m width and a tree canopy cover of trees between 5% and 10%. Or The canopy cover of trees less than 5% but the combined cover of shrubs, bushes and trees more than 10%; includes area of shrubs and bushes where no trees are present.

class.name: Glacier
class.definition: Perennial ice in movement.

class.name: Bare rock
class.definition: Non-vegetated areas with a rock surface.

class.name: Grassland
class.definition: Areas covered by herbaceous vegetation with cover ranging from Closed to Open (15–100%). This category includes rangeland and pasture that is not considered cropland.

class.name: Snow
class.definition: This class describes perennial snow (persistence > 9 months per year).

class.name: Bare soil
class.definition: A soil surface devoid of any plant material.

class.name: Riverbed
class.definition: A tract of land without vegetation surrounded by the waters of an ocean, lake, or stream; it usually includes any accretion in a river course.
